Foot & mouth disease - UK 20010220.0325
Foot & mouth disease - UK (19) 20010307.0470
Date: 10 Mar 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Telegraph, 10 Mar 2001 [edited
http://www.telegraph.co.uk.html>

Emergency measures to save spring lambs by allowing farmers to move
sheep, trapped in fields by Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD) controls, were
announced by the Government yesterday as the epidemic continued to
tighten its grip.
As the number of confirmed cases in the United Kingdom rose to 127, an
increase of 20 on the previous day, Jim Scudamore, the Government's Chief
Veterinary Officer, admitted farms had been hit by a "second wave" of
infection. Sheep and cattle which had been infected with the disease by
earlier known victims were only now showing symptoms.
Mr Scudamore said control orders and the movement of livestock which were
due to end on Friday would have to be extended for an indefinite period.
The number of cattle and sheep and pigs culled or awaiting destruction rose
to more than 100 000. Asked whether the epidemic was now out of control Mr
Scudamore, who said the disease would be around for a long time, replied:
"It depends what you mean by out of control."
While the emergency ban on livestock movements imposed by the Government
at the start of the epidemic had stopped the widespread dispersal of the
disease, the virus was striking more animals within herds and flocks
connected in some way with the earliest outbreaks. These outbreaks are
believed to have been spread by sheep traded through a number of markets.
The earliest known cases of the disease were on a pig farm at
Heddon-on-the-Wall, Northumberland. Large numbers of sheep had been moved
in the days before the outbreak was first spotted, and MAFF were still
tracing all of them. Mr Scudamore said: "There is no perception of how
much movement or mixing of sheep has gone on. The crucial question is are
there many more [undiscovered diseased farms and if so how many of these
are incubating the disease which we have not yet found. That's the
question which we accept we cannot answer."
Under the new animal welfare measures farmers will be able to apply for
licences to move pregnant stock in infected and controlled areas - but
not within a radius of about 2 miles (3 kilometres) of an infected farm.
Farmers and animal welfare organizations, including the Royal Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, had called for measures to protect
ewes and sows about to give birth. Many sheep and pigs need to be moved
to sheltered quarters to ensure their offspring are kept warm to enable
farmers and vets to give speedy assistance.
The new licences will cover the movement of animals up to just 0.5km in
cases such as moving dairy cattle and of no more than 5km for pregnant
ewes. Ben Gill, president of the National farmers' Union of England and
Wales, welcomed the new animal measures. "The decision will allow some
desperate farmers to move animals to fresh pastures or gather in sheep
from remote fields for lambing."
An emergency maternity unit for ewes was set up in a catering marquee in
a field in Northamptonshire yesterday. Last night the first of 60 ewes
belonging to Philip Bott of Cold Ashby, near Northampton, was in the last
stages of labor. The marquee is expected to be full of lambs within days.
