[2
Date: 10 Mar 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC, 10 Mar 2001 [edited
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/newsid_1212000/1212579.stm>

Farm leaders are urging the slaughter and disposal of animals affected by
Foot-and-Mouth Disease (FMD) to be speeded up, as the number of new cases
shows no signs of easing. The National Farmers' Union says some of its
members have waited for days before Ministry of Agriculture officials
arrived to oversee the destruction of
potentially infectious livestock.
Confirmed cases were climbing again on Saturday, with the total reaching
139 by the evening.
The government's chief veterinary officer, Jim Scudamore, said the speed
and scale of the infection had come as a shock. "It is a very rapid spread
throughout the whole country," Mr Scudamore said, noting well over a 100
cases had now been confirmed in only a fortnight.
Junior agriculture minister Baroness Hayman said a scheme for rendering
rather than burning carcasses on farms was now operational, using a single
plant in Cheshire. But MAFF dismissed fears of moving infected carcasses to
the rendering plant could mean the contagious disease spreading to areas
previously unaffected. A spokesman said: "These are sealed leak-proof
lorries [trucks being used - if there was a risk we wouldn't be doing it."
New cases were confirmed on Saturday at 4 farms in Cumbria, 3 in Scotland,
2 in Devon, 2 in Co Durham and 1 in Anglesey, bringing the day's total to
12. Friday was the worst day yet in terms for confirmed outbreaks, with 20
new cases announced by the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food
(MAFF). The tally shattered hopes the disease, which typically has a 14 day
incubation period, would peak by Thursday.
It is now thought the virus is being harbored by sheep, in which it is more
difficult to spot than in cattle or pigs.
According to the latest MAFF figures, the total number of animals facing
slaughter is now 114 000, of which 82 000 have already been killed.
